New DB title:  S.rivolianaGenomeAssemblies
Sequence type: Nucleotide
Keep MBits: T
Maximum file size: 1000000000B
Adding sequences from FASTA; added 1343 sequences in 10.2362 seconds.
2. Step 1 created three new files
  1. SerRivdb.nhr
  2. SerRivdb.nin
  3. SerRivdb.nsq
3. I moved these three files into a new folder
  1. 04_BlastDatabase2


  I now have my Blast database in the appropriate file so I will change my working directory to
  /Users/amberleighhenschen/GithubRepos/Learning-Bioinformatics/IntroductionToBlast/04_BlastDatabase2

Steps:
1. Create a soft link to the benediniaGene.fasta file
  1. ln -s ../benediniaGene.fasta
  2. Would this have worked for creating the blast database by soft linking the S.rivolianaGenomeAssemblies file?
2. Creating a soft link did not work as I am getting an error saying that the benediniaGene.fasta file is not accessible.
  1. Why does this not work???
3. To make the benediniaGene.fasta file accessible I made a copy of it in the 04_BlastDatabase2 folder.
  1. Working directory for this action: /Users/amberleighhenschen/GithubRepos/Learning-Bioinformatics/IntroductionToBlast/01_ClectinGeneFasta
  2. Code: cp benediniaGene.fasta /Users/amberleighhenschen/GithubRepos/Learning-Bioinformatics/IntroductionToBlast/04_BlastDatabase2
4. Blasted the C-lectin protein sequence and put the output into a new file, blastout.txt
  1. tblastn -db SerRivdb -query benediniaGene.fasta  -out blastout.txt
5. Used nano to look at new file
  1. nano blastout.txt
6. Created a second file, blastout2.txt, with out specific outputs
  1. tblastn -db SerRivdb -query benediniaGene.fasta  -outfmt '6 qseqid sseqid pident length mismatch gapopen qstart qend sstart send evalue bitscore qcovs salltitles' -num_threads 16 -out blastout2  .txt
7. Used more command to filter only results that have at least 50% identity with our protein sequences
  1. more blastout2.txt  | awk '$3>50'
